  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\det(g)\\big|_{p}=0,\n\\qquad\ng^{-1}\\big|_{p}\\ \\text{does not exist},\n\\qquad\n\\det(g)\\neq 0\\ \\text{for}\\ x\\neq p .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nA metric tensor $g$ admits an inverse $g^{-1}$ precisely when its determinant is nonzero:\n\n\\begin{equation}\ng^{-1}\\ \\text{exists}\n\\iff\n\\det(g)\\neq 0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\nThe Trawinistic manifold is ordinary away from $p$, so:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\det(g)(x)\\neq 0,\n\\qquad x\\neq p .\n\\end{equation}\n\nAt the TZP, invertibility fails. Hence:\n\n\\begin{equation}\ng^{-1}\\big|_p \\ \\text{does not exist}.\n\\end{equation}\n\nBy the determinant criterion, this implies:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\det(g)\\big|_p=0 .\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nID 0004 strengthens ID 0001 by explicitly separating the ordinary region from the TZP degeneracy region.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
